%N A387334 Number of addition sums of the form x + y = z with 0 < x < y in base n, where each digit of the base appears at most once among all of x, y and z.
%C A387334 If the restriction x < y is removed then there are exactly twice as many results.
%C A387334 Results for n = 13 calculated independently by Markus Kroetzsch and Denny Vrandecic, results for n = 14 to 20 calculated solely by Markus Kroetzsch.
%e A387334 The a(4) = 1 addition sum in base 4 is 1 + 2 = 3.
%e A387334 The a(5) = 6 addition sums in base 5 are:
%e A387334   1 +  2 =  3,
%e A387334   1 +  3 =  4,
%e A387334   2 +  3 = 10,
%e A387334   3 +  4 = 12,
%e A387334   1 + 24 = 30,
%e A387334   4 + 21 = 30.
%o A387334 (PARI) A387334(n)={ sum(Lx=1,n\3, sum(Ly=Lx, (n-Lx)\2, my(cnt=0, ii=2+(Lx<3)*Lx, dz); forvec(dxy=vector(Lx+Ly,i, [Ly<3, n-1]), forperm(if(dxy[1], dxy, concat([dxy[2..ii], 0, dxy[ii+1..-1]])), d, (d[Lx+1] && d[#d] && d[Lx]) || next; Lx<Ly || d[1]<d[Lx+1] || (d[1]<dxy[#dxy] && next) || break; #(dz=digits(fromdigits(d[1..Lx],n)+fromdigits(d[-Ly..-1],n),n))==#(dz=Set(dz)) && !#setintersect(dz,dxy) && cnt++),2); cnt))} \\ _M. F. Hasler_, Sep 06 2025
